C.definition: Degrees of points in computable metric spaces. They contain a set of the form $\bigoplus_{n\in \omega} \{q\in \mathbb{Q}\ |\ q<\alpha_n\}\oplus \{q\in \mathbb{Q}\ |\ q>\alpha_n}$, where $\{\alpha_n\}_{n<\omega}$ is a member of Hilbert cube [0,1]^{\omega}.
C.label: continuous

implication.description: continuous $\rightarrow$ not half of a nontrivial $K$-pair

justification.direct: Joe Miller (2003) proves that continuous degree cannot be quasiminimal. In fact, the total degrees bounded by a nontotal continuous degree form a Scott set.
Joe Miller (2004) proved the existence of nontotal continuous degrees. His proof uses a variant of Brower's fixed point theorem for multivalued functions.

One of the initial examples of cototal degrees given by Andrews, Ganchev, Kuyper, Lempp, Miller, Soskova, and Soskova (ta) are the continuous degrees. The proof relies on the fact that $\{q\ | q<\alpha\}\oplus\{q\ | q>\alpha\} \leq_e \{q\ | q\leq\alpha\}\oplus\{q\ | q\geq\alpha\} \equiv_e \overline{\{q\ | q<\alpha\}\oplus\{q\ | q>\alpha\} } $

Cai, Lempp, Miller, and Soskova (2014 unpublished) observed that if $\alpha$ and $x$ are real numbers such that the continuous degree of $x$ is not below the continuous degree of $\alpha$ then $\alpha+x$ is not rational. Continuous degrees of sequences in Hilbert cube with no rational members have total continuous degree. See Andrews, Igusa, Miller, and Soskova (ta) for a proof.
Easy to see from definition.

If $A$  and $\overline A$ are not bounded by $\emptyset'$ then $A\oplus \emptyset'$ and $\overline{A}\oplus \emptyset'$ form a minimal pair relative to $\emptyset'$  and hence $A$ is incomparable with its skip. Cototal degrees are bounded by their skips.
